âš–ï¸ Letâ€™s break it down:
1. RMSE is low â†’ The model makes small errors on average
âœ… This means itâ€™s getting close to the actual price move, often in the correct direction.

2. RÂ² â‰ˆ 0 â†’ Itâ€™s not capturing the full spread (variance)
ğŸš« This means itâ€™s not scaling with the magnitude of moves. When thereâ€™s a big move, it probably underpredicts it. When thereâ€™s a tiny move, it might overpredict a bit â€” resulting in overall variance miss even if direction is right.

ğŸ’¡ Interpretation of OBV Deviation "Whiplash" Signal:

Behavior	Evidence
Predicts direction	RMSE much lower than null
Misses magnitude	RÂ² near 0, high residual spread
Causal structure?	OBV lag changes â†’ small price reactions
It likely acts as a â€œtriggerâ€ signal â€” saying "a move is coming", but not necessarily how big it will be.

