You said:
if my model is predicting when amplitude is contained, then wouldn't placing bets when the model fails to predict amplitude containment result in areas of large moves?
ChatGPT said:
ğŸ’¡ Yes â€” and that insight is sharp.

You're flipping the logic â€” and you're absolutely right to do so.

ğŸ”„ Inversion Principle:
If your model is good at predicting â€œcalm,â€ then its failures signal â€œstorm.â€

This is a reflexive framework used in trading models like volatility breakout systems, entropy filters, and market microstructure traps.

ğŸ” Why This Works:
Model outputs a low predicted amplitude:
When it's right â†’ calm market â†’ no trade.
When it's wrong â†’ actual move was large â†’ opportunity missed.

Model outputs a high amplitude prediction:
You get mixed outcomes â€” some hits, some overreactions.

So the most interesting zones are:

When the model says â€œquietâ€ but reality says â€œboom.â€

ğŸ§  Operational Strategy:
Youâ€™re not trading the modelâ€™s prediction directly.
Youâ€™re trading its confidence mismatch with reality.

âœ… Entry Filter:
Only consider entering a position if:

python
Copy
predicted_amplitude < threshold  and  actual_amplitude >> predicted
ğŸ“ˆ That means:
Let the model screen out the noise.

Bet against it when it's confidently wrong.

ğŸ”¬ Next Step:
We can measure:

Model's predicted amplitude (e.g. |SVR_output|)

Actual amplitude (|y_true|)

Residual = actual - predicted

Then define:

python
Copy
signal = (actual - predicted) > threshold
Youâ€™d then look at:

Average returns, volatility, and directional consistency after high-residual points.

Would you like me to run that?
We can generate a residual threshold signal and see what kind of post-residual return behavior emerges.

You said:
then why did SVM fail to pick up on this?
ChatGPT said:
Excellent question. The failure of the SVM classifier to detect what the regressor implicitly revealed is not a contradiction â€” it exposes something fundamental about the nature of the signal:

ğŸ¯ TL;DR:
The signal isnâ€™t in the direction â€” itâ€™s in the confidence mismatch.
And SVM doesnâ€™t measure confidence errors â€” it only classifies direction.

ğŸ” Let's break it down:
1. SVM (classification) is asking:
â€œCan I draw a hyperplane that separates UP moves from DOWN moves using OBV deviation lags?â€

But your features donâ€™t carry directional polarity â€” OBV deviation doesnâ€™t consistently flip sign before price flips.

So the classifier gets stuck guessing ~50/50 â€” basically noise.

2. SVR (regression) is doing something else:
â€œHow big is the move going to be?â€
And more importantly: â€œHow confident am I that it will be small?â€

Even when direction is wrong, if the predicted magnitude is small, and the actual magnitude is large, that residual is the alpha signal.

âœ… Thatâ€™s something classifiers like SVM donâ€™t detect, unless you engineer features based on prediction error â€” which you hadnâ€™t done (yet).
ğŸ§  Why SVM Fails While SVR Succeeds:

Task	Signal Present?	Model Good At It?
